INSERT INTO `coursemanagement_maincontent` (`id`, `topic`, `content`, `estimated_time`, `sub_topic`, `slug`) VALUES
(1, 'Word', '<h1><strong>Word</strong></h1>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"100+ Word Pictures | Download Free Images on Unsplash\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In both written and spoken language, a <strong>word </strong>refers to a speech sound or a combination of two or more speech sounds. In linguistics, a word serves as a sign to represent/refer to something or someone in order to convey a certain meaning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A <strong>word</strong> is a single linguistic unit. <strong>Verbs, nouns, adjectives, and adverbs</strong> are the four main <strong>word classes</strong>. A <strong>sentence</strong> is the most fundamental unit of grammar, consisting of a subject, a verb phrase, and, occasionally, a compliment. A <strong>sentence</strong> is a grammatical unit. There must be at least one main clause in it. A <strong>sentence</strong> starts with a capital letter and concludes with a full stop in writing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples: &lsquo;love&rsquo;, &lsquo;cricket&rsquo;, &lsquo;sky&rsquo; etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A speech sound, or a combination of speech sounds, must meet many characteristics in order to be considered a <strong>word</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Between two words, there must be a potential stop in voice and a space in written form. Assume that the words &#39;ball&#39; and &#39;bat&#39; are not interchangeable. As a result, if we employ them in a sentence, we must allow for a possible pause after each one. It cannot be like &ldquo;Ilikeplayingcricket&rdquo;. If we take pause, these sounds can be regarded as four distinct words which are &lsquo;I&rsquo;, &lsquo;like&rsquo;, &rsquo;playing&rsquo;, cricket&rsquo;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least one root must be present in every word. It can no longer be a word if this root is broken. The word &#39;unfaithful,&#39; for example, comes from the root &#39;faith.&#39; These sounds will not be considered words if we separate &#39;faith&#39; into &#39;fa&#39; and &#39;ith.&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every word must have a meaning. In the <strong>English language</strong>, for example, the sound &#39;bhanana&#39; has no meaning. As a result, it isn&#39;t an English term.</p>', 1, 'Word: The Definition & Criteria', 'word'),
(2, 'Sentence', '<h1>Sentence</h1>\r\n<p>A <strong>sentence</strong> is a word or a set of words that represents a complete thought by making a statement/order, asking a question, or proclaiming.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She is a good girl (statement), Is she a good girl? (question), What nice weather! (exclaiming).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Simple sentence</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>simple sentence</strong> must have a single clause (a single verb) that is independent, and it cannot take another clause.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I always wanted to become a writer. (One clause &ndash; one verb)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Compound sentence</h2>\r\n<p>There must be more than one independent clause in a <strong>compound sentence</strong> and no dependent clauses.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>I always wanted to become a writer</strong>, and <strong>she wanted to become a doctor</strong>. (Two independent clauses &ndash; two verbs)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Complex sentence</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>complicated sentence</strong> can have several clauses, but only one of them must be an independent clause, and the others must be dependent clauses (es).</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>I know </strong>that<strong> you always wanted to be a writer.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Compound-complex sentence</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>compound-complex</strong> sentence (also known as a <strong>complex&ndash;compound sentence</strong>) combines the characteristics of both compound and complicated sentences into a single statement.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>I know</strong> that <strong>you always wanted to become a writer</strong>, but <strong>I always wanted to become a doctor</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Functionally, sentences are of mainly four types:</p>\r\n<h2>Declarative sentence</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Declarative sentence</strong> simply communicates a thought or emotion, makes a declaration, or characterizes something.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I want to be a good singer. (a statement)</li>\r\n<li>I am very happy today. (a feeling)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Imperative sentence</h2>\r\n<p>An <strong>imperative phrase</strong> is used to make a request or issue an order. Although most imperative sentences conclude with a period (i.e., a full stop), they can also end with an exclamation mark under specific circumstances (i.e., exclamation mark).</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Please sit down.</li>\r\n<li>I need you to sit down now!</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Interrogative sentence</h2>\r\n<p>A question is posed via an <strong>interrogative statement</strong>. A note of <strong>interrogation </strong>must be included at the conclusion of <strong>interrogative statements</strong> (i.e., question mark)</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>When are you going to submit your assignment?</li>\r\n<li>Do you know him?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Exclamatory sentence</h2>\r\n<p>An <strong>exclamatory statement</strong> conveys an emotional outburst. These feelings might include joy, awe, grief, wrath, and so forth.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>What a day it was!</li>\r\n<li>I cannot believe he would do that!</li>\r\n</ul>', 1.5, 'Sentence: Definition & Types', 'sentence'),
(3, 'Speech', '<h1>Parts of Speech</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The division of <strong>words into parts of</strong> <strong>speech</strong> is based on their roles and functions within the language\'s structure.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Noun</h2>\r\n<p>People, places, objects, ideas, concepts, and so on are all <strong>nouns</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples: <strong>Aashish</strong> is a good boy.&nbsp; <strong>Pokhara</strong> is the best <strong>city</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Pronoun</h2>\r\n<p>Instead of using the same noun(s)/noun phrase again and over, a <strong>pronoun</strong> is used to refer to a noun/noun phrase, or nouns/noun phrases (s).</p>\r\n<p>Examples: Nikesh is a good boy. <strong>He</strong> gets up early in the morning.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Verb</h2>\r\n<p>The <strong>verb</strong> denotes an action or a state that is continuing. It is the most important part of a statement.</p>\r\n<p>Examples: Neha is going home. She <strong>loves</strong> his home.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Adjective</h2>\r\n<p><strong>An adjective</strong> modifies or describes nouns in a sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Examples: Ashmita loves his<strong> beautiful</strong> daughters. Her daughters also love their <strong>caring </strong>mothers.</p>\r\n<h2>Adverb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Adverbs</strong> are adjectives, verbs, or other adverbs that modify or describe other adjectives, verbs, or other <strong>adverbs</strong>. It provides answers to the following questions: When, Where, and How? or how much is it?</p>\r\n<p>Examples: He is running <strong>fast</strong>.&nbsp; He<strong> always</strong> reads <strong>attentively</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Preposition</strong> gives context to nouns in relationship to other nouns or pronouns.</p>\r\n<p>Examples: I am going <strong>to</strong> Denmark. Denmark is<strong> in</strong> Europe.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Conjunction</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>conjunction</strong> is a word that joins nouns, noun phrases, clauses, or sentences.</p>\r\n<p>Examples: Gita loves chocolate<strong> and</strong> chips. She loves pasta, <strong>but</strong> she hates pizza.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Interjection</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Interjections</strong> are short, sudden pauses in a speech that are typically used to indicate emotion.</p>\r\n<p>Examples: <strong>Oh!</strong> That feels terrible. <strong>Alas!</strong> They have lost the match.</p>', 1, 'Parts of speech', 'speech'),
(4, 'Noun', '<h1>Nouns</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A <strong>noun</strong> is a term that describes something (a book), a person (Betty Crocker), an animal (a cat), a location (Omaha), a trait (softness), an idea (justice), or an activity. It\'s usually a single word, but it\'s not always: nouns include cake, shoes, school bus, and time and a half.</p>\r\n<p>There are two main types of nouns: <strong>common nouns</strong> and <strong>proper nouns.</strong></p>\r\n<h2>Common and Proper Nouns</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Common nouns</strong> are words for persons, places, and objects. Unless they occur at the beginning of a sentence, they are not capitalized. <strong>Proper nouns</strong> are names for distinct individuals, places, things, or concepts. <strong>Proper nouns</strong> should be capitalized at all times.</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>Common </strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>Proper</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>town</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>Kathmandu</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>doctor</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>Doctor Suman Raj</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>car</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>BMW</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>boy</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>Suman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Singular and Plural Noun</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Use a <strong>singular noun</strong> when talking about a single thing or person. When talking about two or more persons, places, or things, use a <strong>plural noun</strong>.</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>a taxi</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>taxis</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>bus</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>buses</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>a mountain</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>mountains</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>an uncle</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>uncles</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>an oven </strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>ovens</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>* Nouns</strong> that end in <strong>s, ss, ch, sh </strong>or<strong> x</strong>, are made plural by adding <strong>es</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Fox: foxes, bus: buses, dress: dresses, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Most <strong>nouns</strong> that end in <strong>y</strong> are made plural by changing the <strong>y</strong> to <strong>i</strong> and adding <strong>es</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Baby: babies, story: stories, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Nouns that have a <strong>vowel</strong> before the y are made plural by simply adding s at the end.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Boy: boys, day: days, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Many nouns that end in f are made plural by changing the f to v and adding es.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Wolf: wolves, thief: thieves, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Most nouns that end in fe are made plural by changing the f to v and adding s.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Life: lives, knife: knives, etc.</p>\r\n<h2>Collective Nouns</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Collective nouns</strong> are words for groups of people, animals, or things.</p>\r\n<p>Example of collective nouns:</p>\r\n<p>A family, a crew, the army, etc.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Masculine and Feminine Nouns</h2>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Masculine nouns</strong> are terms that refer to men, boys, and animals that are male.</p>\r\n<p>Women, girls, and female animals are all referred to as <strong>feminine nouns</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>Masculine </strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>Feminine</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>husband</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>wife</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>pupil</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>parent</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>boy</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>girl</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>son</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>daughter</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p><strong>dancer</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"312\">\r\n<p>manager</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 2, 'Noun & Types of Noun', 'noun'),
(5, 'Pronoun', '<h1>Pronouns</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A <strong>pronoun</strong> is a term that replaces a noun or noun phrase in a sentence. <strong>Pronouns</strong> refer to either a previously specified noun or a noun that does not need to be named expressly.</p>\r\n<h2>Personal Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p>Personal pronouns can be employed as a<strong> subject of verb or as the object of verb</strong>.</p>\r\n<h2>Subject Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p>The subject of a verb performs the verb\'s action<strong>. I, you, he, she, it, we</strong>, and they are all personal pronouns that can be used as the subject of a verb.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Priya</strong> loves dogs. <strong>She</strong> has two dogs.</p>\r\n<p>The subject of the verb <strong>loves</strong> in the first sentence is the proper noun <strong>Priya</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>The pronoun <strong>she</strong> is the subject of the verb in the second phrase <strong>has.</strong></p>\r\n<h2>Object Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p>The <strong>verb\'s action</strong> is received by the <strong>verb\'s object</strong>. <strong>Me, you, him, she, it, us, and them</strong> are all personal pronouns that can be used as the object of a verb.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Priya</strong> loves dogs. She likes to stroke <strong>them.</strong></p>\r\n<p>The noun <strong>cats</strong> is the subject of the verb <strong>likes</strong> in the first sentence. The pronoun <strong>them</strong> is the object of the verb <strong>stroke</strong> in the second sentence.</p>\r\n<h2>First Person, Second Person and Third Person</h2>\r\n<p>We usually speak in the <strong>first person</strong> while discussing ourselves, our ideas, and the events that occur in our lives. The person (or people) being addressed is the subject of the <strong>second-person</strong> point of view. This is the \"you\" point of view. The person (or people) being discussed is the subject of the <strong>third-person</strong> point of view.</p>\r\n<table width=\"651\">\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"7\">\r\n<p>Personal Pronouns</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td rowspan=\"2\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n<p>Subject</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n<p>Object</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n<p>Possessive</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Singular</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Plural</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Singular</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Plural</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Singular</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Plural</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>1st&nbsp;Person</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>I</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>we</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>me</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>us</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>my, mine</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>our, ours</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>2nd&nbsp;Person</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>you</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>you</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>you</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>you</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>your, yours</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>your, yours</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>3rd&nbsp;Person</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>he, she, it</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>they</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>him, her, it</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>them</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>his, her, hers, its</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>their, theirs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Possessive Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p>When talking about objects that belong to individuals, <strong>possessive pronouns</strong> are employed. <strong>Possessive pronouns</strong> include mine, yours, his, hers, ours, and theirs.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>This pencil is <strong>mine</strong> and that one is <strong>his</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Priya has lost her cat. Is this cat <strong>hers?</strong></p>\r\n<h2>Demonstrative Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Demonstrative pronouns</strong> are used to call attention to something. The <strong>demonstrative pronouns</strong> are this, that, these, and those.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p><strong>This</strong> is my <strong>bench</strong>.</p>\r\n<p><strong>That&rsquo;s</strong> my father&rsquo;s car.</p>\r\n<h2>Interrogative Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p>An <strong>interrogative pronoun</strong> is a pronoun that makes it easier to ask questions. There are just five interrogative pronouns in the English language: - \"what,\" \"which,\" \"who,\" \"whom,\" and \"whose.\"</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who</strong> used all my paper?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who</strong> is Father talking to?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Who</strong> are those people?</p>\r\n<h2>Indefinite Pronouns</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>pronoun</strong> that is indefinite does not relate to a specific person, thing, or amount. It\'s ambiguous and \"indefinite.\" <strong>All, another, any, anyone/anyone, anything, each, everyone/everyone, everything, few, many, nobody, none, one, several, some, someone/someone</strong> are examples of indefinite pronouns.</p>', 1.6, 'Pronoun: Definition & Types', 'pronoun'),
(6, 'Adjective', '<h1>Adjective</h1>\r\n<p><strong>Adjectives</strong> are words that describe the characteristics of nouns. We say that an <strong>adjective</strong> <strong>\"modifies\"</strong> a noun when it describes it. <strong>Adjectives</strong> can be used to describe <strong>emotions or attributes.</strong></p>\r\n<h2>Adjectives modify nouns</h2>\r\n<p>Adjectives are words that <strong>modify (describe) nouns</strong>, according to <strong>most pupils.</strong> <strong>Verbs, adverbs</strong>, and <strong>other adjectives</strong> are not modified by adjectives.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Your cake should have <strong>sixteen</strong></li>\r\n<li>The <strong>scariest</strong> villain of all time is Michael Myers.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The <strong>adjectives</strong> in the preceding phrases are simple to recognize since they appear <strong>just before the nouns they modify.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Adjectives</strong> are often employed to <strong>modify nouns</strong>, although they can also be <strong>used in conjunction with connecting verbs</strong> or the verb to be. A connecting verb is a verb that expresses a state of being or a <strong>sensory experience</strong>, such as <strong>feel</strong>, <strong>seem</strong>, or <strong>taste</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>That buffalo sure is <strong>happy</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Driving is <strong>faster</strong> than walking.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>A predicate adjective</strong> is a <strong>technical word</strong> for this type of <strong>adjective</strong>.</p>\r\n<h2>Uses of adjectives</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Adjectives</strong> inform the reader <strong>how much or how many of anything</strong> you\'re talking about, what you\'d like handed to you, or what type of things you\'d like.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Please use <strong>five yellow flowers</strong> in the arrangement.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Five </strong>and <strong>yellow</strong> are <strong>modifying</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Degrees of comparison</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Absolute</strong>, <strong>comparative</strong>, and <strong>superlative adjectives</strong> are the <strong>three types of adjectives</strong>. <strong>Absolute adjectives</strong> are <strong>adjectives</strong> that describe <strong>something in and of itself</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>A <strong>messy</strong></li>\r\n<li>A <strong>mischievous</strong></li>\r\n<li>A <strong>messier</strong></li>\r\n<li>A more <strong>mischievous</strong></li>\r\n<li>The <strong>messiest</strong></li>\r\n<li>The <strong>most mischievous</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Coordinate adjectives</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>comma</strong> or the word should be used to separate <strong>coordinate adjectives</strong>. When two adjectives in a phrase <strong>modify the same noun</strong>, they are said to be <strong>coordinated</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>This is going to be a <strong>long, hot</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Isobel&rsquo;s <strong>dedicated</strong> and <strong>tireless</strong> efforts made all the difference.</p>', 2, 'Adjective: Definition & Types', 'adjective');
