(7, 'Verb', '<h1>Verb</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A <strong>verb</strong> is a word or a group of words that describes an action, a state of being, or a situation. The component of a phrase that informs us what the subject does is called a <strong>verb</strong>. Many additional elements influence <strong>verbs</strong>, including the subject, person, number, tense, mood, and voice.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Dipesh <strong>is</strong> a good boy. (A state of being)</li>\r\n<li>Niken <strong>is going</strong> to school. (A condition of action)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Basic Forms of Verbs</h2>\r\n<p>There are <strong>six</strong> different types of <strong>verbs</strong>. The following are the forms:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Base form</strong>: Children <strong>play</strong> in the field.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Infinitive</strong>: Tell them not to <strong>play</strong>.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Past tense</strong>: They <strong>played</strong> football yesterday.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Past participle</strong>: I have <strong>eaten</strong> a burger.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Present participle</strong>: I saw them <strong>playing</strong> with him today.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Gerund</strong>: <strong>Swimming</strong> is the best exercise.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Base Verb</h2>\r\n<p>The <strong>basic verb</strong> is a verb that does not have a suffix (-ing, -ed, -en) attached to it. It\'s also known as the Root Verb since it\'s the most basic form of a verb.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Do</strong> your homework.</li>\r\n<li>He <strong>runs</strong> a mile every morning.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Regular Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Regular verbs</strong> are those that have the most often used conjugations. It is regular because it follows most, if not all, of the standard grammatical rules.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Salman plays cricket.</li>\r\n<li>Simran called out my name.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Irregular Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Irregular verbs</strong>, in general, are verbs that contain irregularities in terms of adhering to grammatical norms.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>He <strong>drove</strong> all the way back.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Do</strong> the dishes.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Transitive Verb</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>Transitive Verb</strong> is one that takes a direct object and places it straight after it. They frequently compose the simplest phrases possible.</p>\r\n<p><br /> Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I <strong>love</strong> visiting her home.</li>\r\n<li>He <strong>went</strong> to the fair.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Intransitive Verb</h2>\r\n<p>An <strong>Intransitive Verb</strong> is a primary verb that does not accept a direct object given straight after it and instead mentions an indirect one somewhere down the line.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I laughed.</li>\r\n<li>Suman ran.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Weak Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Weak verbs</strong> are those that terminate in \"-d\" or \"-t\" in their Past Indefinite and Past Participle forms. Although it is common to equate <strong>Weak Verbs</strong> with Regular Verbs, not all <strong>Weak Verbs</strong> in the English language are Regular Verbs.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<table width=\"306\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"180\">\r\n<p><strong>Present Indefinite</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\">\r\n<p><strong>Past Indefinite</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Spend</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\">\r\n<p>Spent</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Walk</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\">\r\n<p>Walked</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Book</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\">\r\n<p>Booked</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Learn</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\">\r\n<p>Learnt</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Want</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"126\">\r\n<p>Wanted</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Strong Verb</h2>\r\n<p>In the Present Indefinite to Past Indefinite to Past Participle form of verbs, <strong>strong verbs</strong> have vowels that shift from I to \"a\" to \"u\" in the verb stem.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<table width=\"385\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p><strong>Present Indefinite</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p><strong>Past Indefinite</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p><strong>Past Participle</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p>Ring</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Rang</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Rung</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p>Drink</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Drank</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Drunk</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p>Cling</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Clang</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Clung</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p>Swim</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Swam</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Swum</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p>Sing</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Sang</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Sung</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"147\">\r\n<p>Wring</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Wrang</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"119\">\r\n<p>Wrung</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>Finite Verbs</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Finite verbs</strong> are the actual verbs that make up a sentence\'s roots. It is a type of verb that is performed by or relates to a subject and utilizes one of the twelve tense forms, which varies depending on the number or person of the subject.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Bijay plays basketball.</li>\r\n<li>They are playing for Nepal.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Non-finite Verbs</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Non-finite verbs</strong> aren\'t really verbs at all. They don\'t function as verbs in sentences; instead, they function as nouns, adjectives, adverbs, and so on. Because non-finite verbs, also known as verbal, have no direct link to the subject, they do not vary according to the number/person of the subject.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Playing football is her only job. (Present participle)</li>\r\n<li>She has a broken fan. (Past participle)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Action Verbs</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Action verbs</strong> describe what the sentence\'s subject does. <strong>Action verbs</strong> can help the listener/reader experience emotions and visualize scenes more clearly and precisely. There are <strong>two</strong> types of <strong>action verbs</strong>:<strong> transitive</strong> and <strong>intransitive</strong>.</p>\r\n<h3>Transitive verbs</h3>\r\n<p>A direct object is required for transitive verbs. A transitive verb necessitates the action of something or someone.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She <strong>painted</strong> her room.</li>\r\n<li>He <strong>is reading</strong> the novel.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Intransitive verbs</h3>\r\n<p>Nothing is acted upon by <strong>intransitive verbs</strong>. An adjective, adverb, preposition, or another component of speech may come after them.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She <strong>smiled</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>I <strong>wake</strong> up at 10 AM.\\</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Linking Verb</h2>\r\n<p>A connecting verb adds information about the sentence\'s topic. It connects the subject and the complement &mdash; that is, the words that come after the <strong>linking verb</strong> &mdash; in its most basic form. Instead of presenting activity, it establishes a connection between them.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The food <strong>seemed</strong></li>\r\n<li>You <strong>look</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Auxiliary Verbs</h2>\r\n<p>Helping verbs are another name for <strong>auxiliary verbs</strong>. <strong>Auxiliary verbs</strong> assist to convey time, tense, and potential by extending the primary verb. Be verbs, have, and do are&nbsp;<strong>auxiliary verbs</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Do</strong> you drink coffee?</li>\r\n<li><strong>Don&rsquo;t</strong> waste your time.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Modal Verbs</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>modal verb</strong> is similar to an auxiliary verb in that it has two parts. It is used to imply possibility, potentiality, capacity, permission, anticipation, and duty in conjunction with the primary verb.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>He<strong> should</strong> call him.</li>\r\n<li>She <strong>will</strong> go there.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Reflexive Verb</h2>\r\n<p>The <strong>Reflexive Verb</strong> occurs when the Subject and Object are the same and the verb reflects on the Subject. These verbs are frequently employed with reflexive pronouns such as myself, he, her, it, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She has done it himself.</li>\r\n<li>She\'ll watch it herself.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Ergative Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Ergative verbs</strong> can be used to express both transitive and intransitive meanings. In English, they\'re referred to as <strong>Labile Verbs</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<table width=\"409\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"197\">\r\n<p><strong>Intransitive Verbs</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"212\">\r\n<p><strong>Transitive Verbs</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"197\">\r\n<p>The door&nbsp;<strong>opens</strong>.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"212\">\r\n<p>I&nbsp;<strong>opened</strong>&nbsp;the door.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"197\">\r\n<p>The bell&nbsp;<strong>rang</strong>.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"212\">\r\n<p>She&nbsp;<strong>rang</strong>&nbsp;the bell.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"197\">\r\n<p>The light is&nbsp;<strong>fused</strong>.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"212\">\r\n<p>They&nbsp;<strong>fused</strong>&nbsp;the lights.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"197\">\r\n<p>The whistle&nbsp;<strong>blew</strong>.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"212\">\r\n<p>Tom&nbsp;<strong>blew</strong>&nbsp;the whistle.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Phrasal Verb</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>Phrasal Verb</strong> is an idiomatic phrase that consists of a Verb and another element, most frequently an Adverb or a Preposition.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I\'ll <strong>see to</strong></li>\r\n<li>She <strong>broke down</strong> in tears.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Lexical Verb</h2>\r\n<p>The main or main verb of a phrase is the <strong>lexical verb</strong>, which generally takes on the main duty of a verb that symbolizes the action of the Noun or Pronoun.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She <strong>ran</strong> to his father.</li>\r\n<li>Atit <strong>tried</strong> her best.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>DE-Lexical Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>De-lexical</strong> verbs are unimportant in terms of meaning since they seldom have meanings on their own when employed alone. The meaning of the verbs is transferred to the noun. <strong>De-lexical verbs</strong> include words like taking, have, make, give, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She <strong>took</strong> a shower.</li>\r\n<li>I <strong>had</strong> a cold coffee.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Stative Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Stative or Being Verbs</strong> are verbs that describe the state of being.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>You <strong>belong</strong> to the pomp and power.</li>\r\n<li>We <strong>remember</strong> what happened that day.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Dynamic Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Dynamic or Fientive Verbs</strong> are verbs that imply the Subject\'s continual or progressive action. They represent the Subject\'s state of movement.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Keep <strong>hitting</strong> the basketball hard.</li>\r\n<li>The cat goes for a <strong>walk</strong> every afternoon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Non-continuous Verb</h2>\r\n<p>The Verbs that are usually never used in their continuous forms are called <strong>Non-continuous Verbs.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<table width=\"544\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p>I&nbsp;<strong>like</strong>&nbsp;to play basketball.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: line-through;\">I\'m liking to play basketball.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p>I&nbsp;<strong>love</strong>&nbsp;to do the chords.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: line-through;\">I\'m loving to do the chords.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p>She does not&nbsp;love&nbsp;you.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: line-through;\">She\'s lovinging you.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: line-through;\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p>He just&nbsp;<strong>feels</strong>&nbsp;a bit dizzy, no need to worry.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"272\">\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: line-through;\">He\'s just feeling a bit dizzy.</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h2>Intensive Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Intensive verbs</strong> are verbs that concentrate their attention solely on the subject. Linking or Copular verbs are other names for <strong>intensive verbs</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>You <strong>seem </strong></li>\r\n<li>She <strong>looks</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Extensive Verb</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Extensive Verbs</strong> are all verbs that do not concentrate solely on the subject of the sentence (as Intensive Verbs do).</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She <strong>hates</strong></li>\r\n<li>She <strong>runs</strong> too fast.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Participle</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>participle</strong> is a verb form in which some of the traits and functions of both verbs are retained while the functions of the Adjectives are adopted.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<h3>Present Participle (Verb + -ing)</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have I become a laughing stock?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Past Participle</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I have taken a hint.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Perfect Participle (Having + Past Participle)</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Having stepped out of my comfort zone, I saw a whole new world.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Gerund</h2>\r\n<p>The Verbs having -ing endings that function like Nouns in sentences are called <strong>Gerunds</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Smoking</strong> is injurious to health.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Walking</strong> is good for health.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Infinitive</h2>\r\n<p>The \'to + verb\' forms are those in which the verbs are at their base or stem forms and are used instead of verbs as <strong>Nouns, Adjectives, or Adverbs</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I wanted <strong>to help</strong> you out.</li>\r\n<li>Are you trying <strong>to go</strong> there?</li>\r\n</ul>', 2.5, 'Verb: Definition & Types', 'verb'),
(8, 'Adverb', '<h1>Adverb</h1>\r\n<p>Adverbs are words (or groups of words) that modify verbs, adjectives, and other adverbs.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She is running <strong>fast</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Neha works <strong>hard</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Clauses and phrases</strong> that alter verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs in a sentence are known as <strong>clauses adverb and phrases adverb</strong>.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She ran toward the bus <strong>until she was tired</strong>. (Adverb Clause)</li>\r\n<li>They were panicked <strong>without any reason</strong>. (Adverb Phrase)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Conjunctive Adverbs</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>conjunctive adverb</strong> <strong>joins</strong> two <strong>phrases or sentences</strong> together. It <strong>illustrates linkages</strong> and enables transitions between concepts. <strong>Connectors</strong> are another name for <strong>conjunctive adverbs</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Last season there was a great drought; <strong>consequently</strong>, we could not grow crops.</li>\r\n<li>We are still confused, however, if the umpires will come.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Sentence Adverbs</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>sentence adverb</strong> introduces and changes the rest of the phrase.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Hopefully</strong>, we will win the match.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Certainly</strong>, I did not think of coming here.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Adverbs of Time/Frequency (When?)</h2>\r\n<p>The <strong>time or frequency</strong> of the activity in the sentence is indicated by <strong>adverbs of time/frequency</strong>. &nbsp;<strong>Time/frequency adverbs include</strong> always, never, often, eventually, now, regularly, occasionally, once, forever, seldom, before, Sunday, Monday, 10 AM, 12 PM, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I will leave <strong>Tuesday</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>He went to school <strong>a little late yesterday</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Adverbs of Place/Direction (Where?)</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Place/direction adverbs</strong> that indicate the <strong>location/direction</strong> of the activity in the sentence. Some typical <strong>adverbs of location/direction include</strong>: across, over, under, in, out, though, backward, there, around, here, sideways, upstairs, in the park, in the field, in that place, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She plays <strong>in the field</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>He is staying <strong>at my home</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Adverbs of Degree (How Much?)</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Adverbs of degree</strong> are adverbs that<strong> reflect the importance/degree/level of the activity</strong> in the phrase. <strong>Adverbs of degree include</strong> complete, almost, totally, less, slightly, most, thoroughly, somewhat, extremely, considerably, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I am <strong>so</strong> excited about the new job.</li>\r\n<li>Rakesh <strong>hardly </strong>studies</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Adverbs of Manner (How?)</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Adverbs</strong> of manner are adverbs that convey the <strong>method/approach/process</strong> <strong>of the activity </strong>in the phrase. <strong>Common adverbs of manner include</strong> beautifully, equally, thankfully, meticulously, neatly, promptly, bitterly, passionately, resentfully, sincerely, charmingly, relentlessly, and so on. The adverbs in this category frequently finish in ly.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Simran is walking <strong>slowly</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>She is running <strong>fast</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>', 3, 'Adverb: Definition & Types', 'adverb'),
(9, 'Preposition', '<h1>Preposition</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A <strong>preposition</strong> is a term that shows how a noun is related to the other words in a sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I am going to <strong>USA</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>They have gone <strong>out of</strong> the city.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Simple Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Simple Prepositions</strong> are prepositions that express the relationship between the Nouns and Pronouns in a sentence and the remainder of the words in the phrase.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<table width=\"582\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" width=\"582\">\r\n<p><strong>Most Popular Prepositions</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"96\">\r\n<p>and</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>but</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"102\">\r\n<p>at</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>to</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>on</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>in</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"96\">\r\n<p>for</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>of</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"102\">\r\n<p>up</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>off</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>from</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>out</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"96\">\r\n<p>with</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>during</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"102\">\r\n<p>down</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>below</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>beside</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>over</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"96\">\r\n<p>by</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>near</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"102\">\r\n<p>behind</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>inside</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"108\">\r\n<p>among</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"84\">\r\n<p>along</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Double Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Two simple prepositions</strong> combine to make a <strong>single preposition</strong> that connects the Noun(s) or Pronoun(s) to the remainder of the words in a phrase.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Are they out of your mind?</li>\r\n<li>He&rsquo;s sandwiched in between two of her cousins.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Compound Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Compound Prepositions</strong> are made up of both prepositions and other words. Because both require additional prepositions or words to make them function like a preposition, <strong>Compound Prepositions </strong>and<strong> Double Prepositions</strong> are often mistaken.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>According </strong>to my calculations, this color should work just fine.</li>\r\n<li><strong>On behalf of</strong> our family, my father attended the family reunion.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Participle Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Participle Prepositions</strong> are <strong>Present Participles (-ing)</strong> and <strong>Past Participles (-ed and -en)</strong> that are used as Prepositions instead of verbs. These are both <strong>participles and prepositions</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table width=\"541\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p><strong>Present Participle Prepositions</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p><strong>Past Participles Prepositions</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p>Assuming</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p>Respected</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p>Barring</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p>Given</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p>Considering</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p>Gone</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p>During</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p>Barred</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p>Notwithstanding</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p>Provided</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"282\">\r\n<p>Regarding</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"259\">\r\n<p>Taken</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Disguised Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Prepositions are frequently disguised</strong> as other words in the English language. In sentences, these prepositions are frequently disguised as \"a\" and \"o.\"</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Tina visits the riverbank once a day. (in a day)</li>\r\n<li>Keep striding ahead. (on the head)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Detached Preposition</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Detached Preposition</strong> refers to a preposition that has been detached and placed at the conclusion of a sentence.<br /> Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Where are you coming <strong>from</strong>?</li>\r\n<li>won\'t tolerate being screamed<strong> at</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Prepositions of Time</h2>\r\n<p>The link of time between the nouns and the other components of a sentence is shown by <strong>prepositions of time</strong>. The most common <strong>time prepositions</strong> are on, at, in, from, to, for, since, ago, before, till/until, by, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The company called meeting <strong>on 10 January</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>She has been ill <strong>since Friday</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Prepositions of Place and Direction</h2>\r\n<p>The link of location between nouns and the other components of a sentence is shown by <strong>prepositions of place</strong>. The most common <strong>prepositions of place/direction</strong> are on, at, in, by, from, to, towards, up, down, across, between, among, though, in front of, behind, above, over, under, below, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I live <strong>across the river</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>He is <strong>at home</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Prepositions of Agents or Things</h2>\r\n<p>A causal link between nouns and other components of the sentence is indicated by <strong>prepositions of agents or objects</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She is playing <strong>with her sisters</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>This article is <strong>about iPhone</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h2>Phrasal Prepositions</h2>\r\n<p>A <strong>phrasal preposition</strong> is a combination of two or more words that operate as a preposition, rather than a <strong>prepositional phrase</strong>. The most prevalent <strong>phrasal prepositions</strong> are together with, apart from, because of, by means of, according to, in front of, opposed to, in spite of, on account of, in relation to, in addition to, in respect to, instead of, on top of, out of, with regard to, and so on.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I&rsquo;m going <strong>out of</strong> the place.</li>\r\n<li><strong>According to</strong> the new rules, you are right.</li>\r\n</ul>', 2.5, 'Preposition: Definition & Types', 'preposition'),
(10, 'Use of Prepositions', '<h1>Use of Prepositions</h1>\r\n<h2>OF</h2>\r\n<p><strong>Of</strong> expresses the relationship of a part of something to its whole. It is the most used preposition in English.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Most <strong>of the guests</strong> are gone.</li>\r\n<li>He is a boy <strong>of 10</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>ABOUT</h2>\r\n<p><strong>\'On the subject of\'</strong> or <strong>\'concerning of\'</strong> something/someone implies <strong>\'on the subject of\'</strong> or <strong>\'concerning of\'</strong> something/someone. It can also imply \'roughly.\'</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>This article is <strong>about laptops</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>I was <strong>about to leave</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>FOR</h2>\r\n<p>\'With the intention or purpose of\' is the definition of <strong>for</strong>. It denotes that something/someone is suitable <strong>for </strong>its intended function.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>I have done it <strong>for my benefit</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>Take my gratitude <strong>for your kind hospitality</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>WITH</h2>\r\n<p><strong>With</strong> denotes the presence of something or someone.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It is free <strong>with this product</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>I have brought some candies <strong>with me</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>BY</h2>\r\n<p>Something or someone is referred to as <strong>\'as a means of\'</strong> something or someone. In a passive statement, this preposition is frequently used.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>She was undone <strong>by me</strong>.</li>\r\n<li>The letter was written <strong>by her</strong>.</li>\r\n</ul>', 1.5, 'Time, Place & Direction', 'use-of-prepositions'),
(11, 'Conjunction', '<h1>Conjunction</h1>\r\n<p>A conjunction is the <strong>phrases</strong> that <strong>join</strong> sentences into one. Conjunctions <strong>let you</strong> <strong>shape</strong> complex, <strong>stylish</strong> sentences and <strong>keep away from</strong> the choppiness of <strong>more than one</strong> <strong>quick</strong> sentence. Make <strong>positive</strong> that the <strong>terms</strong> joined <strong>with the aid of using</strong> conjunctions are parallel (<strong>proportion</strong> the <strong>identical</strong> structure).</p>\r\n<p>Example &ndash; I love eating and reading comics.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Here &ldquo;and&rdquo; is the conjunction that has joined two sentences into one.</p>\r\n<p>The conjunction can be categorized into three types. They are</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Coordinating conjunction</li>\r\n<li>Correlative conjunction</li>\r\n<li>Subordinating conjunction</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Coordinating conjunction</p>\r\n<p>Coordinating conjunctions assist you to be a part of words, phrases, and clauses of identical grammatical rank in a sentence. The maximum not unusual place coordinating conjunctions are for, and, nor, but, or, yet, and so; you may consider them through the usage of the mnemonic device.</p>\r\n<p>Example- I would love to play basketball <strong><em>or</em></strong> football.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Correlative conjunction</h2>\r\n<p>Pairs of conjunctions that work together are Correlative conjunctions. Some examples related to Correlative conjunctions are either/or, neither/nor, and not only/but also.</p>\r\n<p>Example &ndash; <strong><em>Neither</em></strong> I am good at swimming <strong><em>nor</em></strong> at diving.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Subordinating Conjunctions</h2>\r\n<p>Subordinating conjunctions be a part of unbiased and established clauses. A subordinating conjunction can sign a cause-and-impact dating, a contrast, or a few different sorts of dating among the clauses. Common subordinating conjunctions are because, since, as, although, though, while, and whereas. In some cases, adverbs, such as after, until, or before can act as a conjunction.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Example &ndash; I will stay <strong><em>until</em></strong> Atit arrives.</p>\r\n<p>Subordinating can also be at the start of a sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Example- As soon as he arrives, I am leaving.</p>', 2, 'Conjunction: Definition & Types', 'conjunction'),
(12, 'Interjection', '<h1>Interjections</h1>\r\n<p>The phrase interjection comes from the Latin phrases inter (among) and jacre (to throw). An interjection is a phrase that you throw in among sentences or mind to specific an unexpected feeling. Some examples of interjections are- ouch, wow, yikes, oh my, etc.</p>\r\n<p>There&rsquo;s no strict rule approximately where in an interjection needs to move on the subject of different sentences. You can use an interjection earlier than or after a sentence that explains what&rsquo;s going on.</p>\r\n<p>Example &ndash; wow! This watch looks good on Rakesh.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; This food looks disgusting yikes!</p>\r\n<h2>Interjections in Sentence</h2>\r\n<p>It&rsquo;s feasible to apply an interjection inside a sentence. When you do, deal with the interjection as a parenthetical detail that&rsquo;s break free the relaxation of the sentence. You can be positioned the interjection inner parentheses or set it off with commas.</p>\r\n<p>Example &ndash; Geez, you look horrible.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>When to Use Interjections</h2>\r\n<p>Because interjections are normally cut loose in different sentences, it&rsquo;s tough to apply them incorrectly. The larger subject is whether or not it&rsquo;s suitable to apply an interjection to your writing. Interjections are great to apply in informal and casual writing. It&rsquo;s k to apply them in speech, too. But keep away from the use of interjections in formal writing due to the fact it could seem that you&rsquo;re now no longer treating the subject seriously.</p>', 1.5, 'Interjection: Definition & Types', 'interjection'),
(13, 'Article', '<h1>Article</h1>\r\n<p>An article is a phrase this is used to suggest that a noun is a noun without describing it. For example, withinside the sentence Nick sold a canine, the thing a suggests that the phrase canine is a noun. Articles also can adjust whatever acts as a noun, which includes a pronoun or a noun phrase.</p>\r\n<p>Articles are categorized into two types</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Definite Articles</li>\r\n<li>Indefinite Articles</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Definite Articles &ndash;</h2>\r\n<p>Use the to identify specific or definite nouns: nouns that represent things, places, ideas, or</p>\r\n<p>persons that can be identified specifically.</p>\r\n<p>Use the with both singular and plural definite nouns.</p>\r\n<p>e.g., the house the houses the business the businesses</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Use the to identify things, places, ideas, or persons that represent a specific or definite group or category.</p>\r\n<p>e.g., The students in Professor Smith&rsquo;s class should study harder.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;The automobile revolutionized travel and industry.</p>\r\n<h2>Indefinite Articles</h2>\r\n<p>Use a or a to identify nouns that are not definite and not specific.</p>\r\n<p>- Think of a and an as meaning any or one among many.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;e.g., a book (any book) a dog (any dog) a cat (one cat) a house (one among many houses)</p>\r\n<p> Use a or an only for singular nouns.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Do not use an article for a plural, indefinite noun.</p>\r\n<p>- Think of a plural, indefinite noun as meaning all.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;e.g., Students should study hard. (All students should study hard.)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>When to use a and when to use an</p>\r\n<p>Decide when to use &lsquo;a&rsquo; or &lsquo;an&rsquo; according to the sound of the noun that follows it.</p>\r\n<p>o &lsquo;a&rsquo; is used before consonant sounds.</p>\r\n<p>e.g., a book a dog</p>\r\n<p>o &lsquo;a&rsquo; is used before a sounded h, a long u, and o with the sound of w.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;e.g., a hat a house a union a uniform a one-hour appointment</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>o an is used before vowel sound (exception in long u).</p>\r\n<p>e.g., an asset an essay an index an onion an umbrella</p>\r\n<p>o an is used when h is silent.</p>\r\n<p>e.g., an honor, an hour.</p>', 2, 'Article: Definition & Types', 'article'),
(14, 'Tense', '<h1>Tense</h1>\r\n\r\n<p>Tenses show the time of action in sentences generally carried out by or targeted across the subject of the sentence. The actions are referred to as verbs. Verbs alternate in keeping with tenses and different issues. As verbs are the most essential factors of English sentences, tenses additionally convey paramount significance in English grammar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tenses</strong>&nbsp;are mainly categorized into three types.</p>\r\n\r\n<h4><strong>1. Present Tense</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<h4><strong>2. Past Tense</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<h4><strong>3. Future Tense</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Present Tense</h1>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Simple present tense</li>\r\n	<li>Present perfect tense</li>\r\n	<li>Present continuous tense</li>\r\n	<li>Present perfect continuous tense</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Past Tense</h1>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Simple past tense</li>\r\n	<li>Past perfect tense</li>\r\n	<li>Past continuous tense</li>\r\n	<li>Past perfect continuous tense</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Future Tense</h1>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Simple future tense</li>\r\n	<li>Future perfect tense</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Future continuous tense</li>\r\n	<li>Future perfect continuous tense</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"height:318px; width:785px\">\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>Verb tenses</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>past</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>present</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:210.625px\">\r\n			<p>future</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>&nbsp;Simple</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She watched videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She watches videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:210.625px\">\r\n			<p>She will be watching videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>Continuous</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She was watching videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She is watching videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:210.625px\">\r\n			<p>She will have watched videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>Perfect</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She had watched videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She has watched videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:210.625px\">\r\n			<p>She would have watched videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>Perfeperfect continuous</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She had been watching videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:182.125px\">\r\n			<p>She has been watching videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"width:210.625px\">\r\n			<p>She would have been watching videos on Netflix.</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>', 1.5, 'Past, Present, Future Tense', 'tense'),
(15, 'Present Tense', '<h1>Present Tense</h1>\r\n<p>A tense expresses a motion this is presently occurring or habitually performed, or a state that presently or generally exists. Present tense can further be categorized into 4 types they are -</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Simple present tense</li>\r\n<li>Present perfect tense</li>\r\n<li>Present continuous tense</li>\r\n<li>Present perfect continuous tense</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Simple present tense </h2>\r\n<p>The simple present tense makes use of the foundation shape of the verb besides while the subject is withinside the third person.</p>\r\n<p>Structure &ndash; Subject + verb1/verb5 + object</p>\r\n<p>E.g. &ndash; Ashutosh plays guitar.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Present perfect tense</p>\r\n<p>The present perfect tense makes use of the verb have or has with the past participle of the verb (for everyday verbs, finishing in -ed, -d, or -t). This tense is used to explain actions or states that join the past to the present.</p>\r\n<p>Structure &ndash;</p>\r\n<p>For example:</p>\r\n<p>She has watched Netflix all day. (Her action was done in past and still continues to do it)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Present continuous tense</p>\r\n<p>The present continuous tense <strong>makes use of</strong> <strong>present</strong> <strong>tense</strong> <strong>kinds of</strong> the verb be with <strong>the present</strong> participle of the verb (<strong>finishing</strong> in &ndash;ing). This <strong>tense</strong> <strong>also</strong> has <strong>some</strong> <strong>distinctive</strong> <strong>makes use of</strong>:</p>\r\n<p>Example</p>\r\n<p>I am working on my assessment.</p>\r\n<p>I am going to Wano Kuni next week.</p>\r\n<h2>Present perfect continuous tense</h2>\r\n<p>The present perfect continuous tense makes use of the word have/has been accompanied by the present participle of the verb (finishing in &ndash;ing). This tense is used to suggest that an action started in the past, has continued to appear up till the current moment, and could possibly continue to appear into the future. Here are examples of sentences that use the present perfect continuous tense:</p>\r\n<p>I have been reading since I was in high school.</p>\r\n<p>Kakashi has been living in Konoha for more than a decade.</p>', 1.5, 'Types of present tense', 'present-tense'),
(16, 'Past Tense', '<h1>Past Tense</h1>\r\n<p>In general, we use past tense verbs to consult states or actions that happened withinside the past. Typically, those verbs imply that an action or state started out withinside the past. Depending on the sort of past tense verb we use, we also can imply that the action or state ended inside the past or it didn&rsquo;t stop and keeps taking place right now. They are categorized into 4 types they are &ndash;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Simple past tense</li>\r\n<li>Past perfect tense</li>\r\n<li>Past perfect tense</li>\r\n<li>Past perfect continuous tense</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Simple past tense</h2>\r\n<p>Usually, the simple past tense is formed by adding -ed or -d to the give up of the root of the verb. Some verbs additionally use a -t variation in which they rather end in -t. We use the simple past tense to refer to states and actions that commenced and absolutely completed withinside the past:</p>\r\n<p>I jogged three miles yesterday.</p>\r\n<p>Monica helped Nik with his math homework.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Past perfect tense</h2>\r\n<p>We <strong>shape</strong> the <strong>past perfect tense</strong> <strong>by</strong> <strong>the use of</strong> the <strong>phrase</strong> had <strong>observed</strong> <strong>by</strong> the <strong>past</strong> participle of a verb (for <strong>normal</strong> verbs, <strong>finishing</strong> in -ed, -d, or &ndash;t).</p>\r\n<p>-I had finished my assessment.</p>\r\n<p>-She told me that Nina had broken her legs.</p>\r\n<p>-If I had brought books, I wouldn&rsquo;t have failed the terminal exam.</p>\r\n<h2>Past continuous tense</h2>\r\n<p>To <strong>shape</strong> the past continuous tense, we use the <strong>past</strong> <strong>tense</strong> of the verb to be <strong>observed</strong> <strong>with the aid of using</strong> <strong>the present</strong> participle of the verb (<strong>finishing</strong> in &ndash;ing). The verb be <strong>should</strong> be <strong>correctly</strong> conjugated <strong>in order that</strong> it <strong>agrees</strong> with the <strong>situation</strong> of the sentence.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>We were reading books when it started raining.</p>\r\n<p>Sam couldn&rsquo;t have broken the device because he was doing his homework at that time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Past perfect continuous tense</h2>\r\n<p>The past perfects continuous tense makes use of the word have been accompanied via way of means of the present participle of the verb (finishing in &ndash;ing). We use the past perfect continuous tense to consult actions/states that commenced withinside the beyond, endured for a period of time, after which absolutely ended with inside the past.:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>My brother had been solving a Rubix cube for 20 minutes when the mean bully distracted it.</p>\r\n<p>Our school had been competing locally for years.</p>', 1.5, 'Types of Past Tense', 'past-tense'),
(17, 'Future Tense', '<h1>Future tense</h1>\r\n<p>Future tense verbs, as their call suggests, inform us that a movement or country will manifest with inside destiny. We can use future tense verbs to each consult with activities that we realize will manifest and activities that we suppose will manifest. Depending on the sentence, you could additionally use future tense verbs to mention that something this is going on now or has come about in the beyond will happen once more in the future.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Simple future tense</li>\r\n<li>Past future tense</li>\r\n<li>Past future tense</li>\r\n<li>Past future continuous tense</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Simple future tense</h2>\r\n<p>The auxiliary verb will follow by the root of the verb in the simple future tense. Example</p>\r\n<p>Will we win the game?</p>\r\n<p>He said that my uncle will visit us tomorrow.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Future perfect tense</h2>\r\n<p>The future perfect tense makes use of the word could have been observed with the aid of using the beyond participle of the verb (for regular verbs, finishing in -ed, -d, or &ndash;t). We use the future perfect tense to mention that a state or action might be absolutely completed before a certain time or earlier than some other event happens. For example:</p>\r\n<p>Nate will have published two books before the age of 18.</p>\r\n<p>Hopefully, we will have set up the studio before 3 o&rsquo;clock.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Future continuous tense</h2>\r\n<p>To shape the future continuous tense, we use the verb word that could be accompanied via way of means of the existing participle of the verb (finishing in &ndash;ing). Typically, we use the future continuous tense to mention that a future action or state will continue to take place over a period of time.</p>\r\n<p>For instance:</p>\r\n<p>Unfortunately, I will be reading for my final exams all day tomorrow.</p>\r\n<p>According to the newsreader, it will be raining heavily all of next week.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Future perfect continuous tense</h2>\r\n<p>The future perfect continuous tense makes use of the word will have been observed with the aid of using the existing participle of the verb (finishing in &ndash;ing). In general, we use this verb stressful to mention that a destiny movement or state can have come about for a period of time earlier than a few different occasions interrupts it or ends it.</p>\r\n<p>For instance:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I will have been practicing my vocal routines for a month by the time I have to perform.</p>\r\n<p>Suman will have been working on his &nbsp;AI project for a while when Atit stops by to help him with it.</p>', 1.5, 'Types of Future Tense', 'future-tense');
