(18, 'Phrases', '<h1>Phrases</h1>\r\n<p>Phrases and clauses are the maximum crucial factors of English grammar. Phrase and clause cowl the entirety a sentence has. Clauses are the middle of sentences and terms give a boost to the sentences to come to be meaningful.</p>\r\n<h2>Types of Phrases</h2>\r\n<p>The phrases are generally of several types.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><strong>Noun Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Adjective Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Adverbial Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Prepositional Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Conjunctional Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Interjectional Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Absolute Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Appositive Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Participle Phrase</strong></li>\r\n<li><strong>Gerund Phrase</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Noun phrase</h2>\r\n<p>It is typically assembled centering a single noun and works as a subject, an item, or a supplement withinside the sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>Ram likes to kick the ball hard when he is on the ground. (An object)</p>\r\n<p>Playing video games is a bad habit.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Adjective Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>Comprised of an adjective and works as a single adjective withinside the sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>Rakesh is a well-behaved man.</p>\r\n<p>He is a man of honor.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Adverbial Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>Modifies the verb or adjective and is used as an adverb.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>The bike runs at a high speed.</p>\r\n<p>He performs very slowly.</p>\r\n<h2>&nbsp;</h2>\r\n<h2>Prepositional Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>It begins with a preposition and helps to connect nouns.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>He sacrificed his fee for the sake of his movie.</p>\r\n<p>In the end, we all have a happy ending.</p>\r\n<p>Note: Prepositional phrases include all other types of phrases.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Conjunctional Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>A Conjunctional word works in conjunction with inside the sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>We have to work hard so that we can move to finals.</p>\r\n<p>I will attend the program provided that you come.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Interjectional Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>Interjectional phrases are interjectional, that contain more than one word.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>What a pleasure! I won the grand prize.</p>\r\n<p>Oh please! Don&rsquo;t mention that again.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Absolute Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>The terms containing Noun or Pronoun followed via way of means of a participle and vital modifiers if any are said as Absolute Phrases. They regulate indefinite instructions and also are known as Nominative Phrases.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>God willing, he&rsquo;ll pass the bike trail test this time.</p>\r\n<p>The cold winter sun had set, we left for the skiing.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Appositive Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>An appositive is a Noun or Pronoun regularly followed through modifiers that take a seat down beside every other Noun or Pronoun to explain it. An Appositive Phrase is fixed of phrases containing an Appositive and it follows or precedes the Noun or Pronoun it identifies or explains.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>My college friend, Saurabh always bunked.</p>\r\n<p>Nami, the worker on duty, wrote the letter.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Participle Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>It is a product of a participle, its modifier(s), and/or the gadgets that whole the feel of the sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Riding fast, I keep looking left and right.</p>\r\n<p>Climbing the tower, she looked at us.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Gerund Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>These include a Gerund, its modifier(s), and the opposite essential elements. The characteristic as Nouns similar to Gerunds themselves and meaning they may be Subjects and Objects of the sentences.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Eating plenty of hot dogs in one sitting is not a great idea.</p>\r\n<p>Doing the laundry gives me cold allergies.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Infinitive Phrase</h2>\r\n<p>These are made out of infinitive verbs (To + base verb) at the side of their modifiers and/or complements.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>We love to work together.</p>\r\n<p>They like to crime mystery problems too much.</p>', 2, 'Phrase: Definition, Types & Examples', 'phrases'),
(19, 'Number', '<h1>Numbers</h1>\r\n<p>In grammar, the number refers to the count of a noun or pronoun.</p>\r\n<p>Example:&nbsp;&nbsp; Boy-boys, wife-wives, my-our, ox-oxen, it-they, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Types of Number:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Singular Number</li>\r\n<li>Plural Number</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2>Singular Number</h2>\r\n<p>It refers to the count of only one of a noun or pronouns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Example: bike, table, uncle, father, tiger, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Plural Number</h2>\r\n<p>It refers to the count of more than one noun or pronoun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Example: cars, tables, bikes, parents, geese, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rules &ndash;</p>\r\n<h3>.<strong> Rule 1:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>In general &ldquo;s&rdquo; is used <strong>on the</strong> <strong>giving up</strong> of <strong>a unique</strong> noun to make it plural</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Pencil</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Pencils</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cow</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cows</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>House</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Houses</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Dog</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Dogs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mobile</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mobiles</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 2:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>If there is&nbsp;<strong>s, sh, ch, x,&nbsp;</strong>and&nbsp;<strong>z</strong>&nbsp;at the end of a word, &ldquo;es&rdquo; needs to use.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Bus</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Buses</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Dish</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Dishes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Branch</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Branches</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Fox</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Foxes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Fez</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Fezes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;Rule 3:</p>\r\n<p><em>While the pronunciation of ch is like &ldquo;k&rdquo;, just &ldquo;s&rdquo; is introduced at the end</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Monarch</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Monarchs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Patriarch</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Patriarchs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Matriarch</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Matriarchs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Stomach</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Stomachs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Hierarch</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Hierarchs</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1 whilst there&rsquo;s a &ldquo;y&rdquo; within side the end and a Consonant earlier than that &ldquo;y&rdquo;, &ldquo;i&rdquo; substitute it and an &ldquo;es&rdquo; thereafter.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Story</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Stories</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Hobby</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Hobbies</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Army</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Armies</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Fly</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Flies</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Baby</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Babies</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:</strong><em>&nbsp;however if there&rsquo;s a vowel in advance of that &ldquo;y&rdquo;, do want to extrade it, only &ldquo;s&rdquo; to add.</em></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\">\r\n<p><strong>Example</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Donkey</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Donkeys</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Toy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Toys</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Day</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Days</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Joy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Joys</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Play</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Plays</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 4:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>&ldquo;v&rdquo; is replaced by&nbsp;<strong>f</strong>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<strong>fe</strong>&nbsp;and adds &ldquo;es&rdquo; to complete.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>thief</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Thieves</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Wife</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Wives</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Knife</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Knives</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Wolf</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Wolves</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Leaf</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Leaves</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1</strong><em>&ldquo;es&rdquo; to be introduced if the noun is completed by &ldquo;o&rdquo; and consonant locations ahead.</em></p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Hero</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Heroes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mango</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mangoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Zero</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Zeroes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Potato</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Potatoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Echo</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Echoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:&nbsp;</strong>however while there&rsquo;s a vowel earlier than that &ldquo;o&rdquo;, only &ldquo;s&rdquo; is enough.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cuckoo</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cuckoos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Bamboo</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Bamboos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Studio</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Studios</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Portfolio</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Portfolios</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cameo</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cameos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Exception 1:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;though there&rsquo;s an &ldquo;o&rdquo; and a consonant in advance of it, a few nouns use only &ldquo;s&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Photo</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Photos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Piano</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Pianos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Radio</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Radios</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Canto</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cantos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Memo</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Memos</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Exception 2:</strong>&nbsp;for some words both &ldquo;s&rdquo; and &ldquo;es&rdquo; can be used.</p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mosquito</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mosquitos/mosquitoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Commando</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Commandos/commandoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Portico</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Porticos/porticoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Calico</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Calicos/calicoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Memento</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mementos/mementoes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 5:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Some require <strong>converting</strong> the middle-vowel of the <strong>phrase</strong> to make it plural.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Man</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Men</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Woman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Women</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Foot</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Feet</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mouse</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mice</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Tooth</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Teeth</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 6:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Some require&nbsp;<strong>en, ren,</strong>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<strong>ne</strong>&nbsp;to add at last to make the word plural.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Ox</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Oxen</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Child</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Children</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Brother</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Brethren (brothers also correct)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cow</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Kine (cows also correct)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Sister</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Sistren (sisters also correct)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1</strong>if &ldquo;man&rdquo; (a noun that <strong>includes</strong> or <strong>greater</strong> <strong>phrases</strong> that <strong>collectively</strong> make a <strong>single</strong> noun), &ldquo;men&rdquo; replaces that &ldquo;man&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Fisherman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Fishermen</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Workman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Workmen</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Boatman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Boatmen</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Man-of-war</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Men-of-war</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Salesman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>salesmen</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:</strong>&nbsp; when to an ethnic group, race or civilian is referred, their &ldquo;s&rdquo; will be used.</p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mussalman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mussalmans</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Brahman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Brahmans</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>German</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Germans</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Norman</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Normans</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 7:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>&ldquo;s&rdquo; needs to be added if there&rsquo;s a &ldquo;ful&rdquo; at the end of a word.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Handful</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Handfuls</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mouthful</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>mouthfuls</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Spoonful</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Spoonfuls</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>armful</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Armfuls</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>cupful</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>cupfuls</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>Part 1:</strong>&nbsp;If a compound noun <strong>includes</strong> <strong>numerous</strong> words, &ldquo;s&rdquo; <strong>involves</strong> joining with <strong>the primary</strong>&nbsp;<strong>part of</strong> that noun.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Brother-in-law</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Brothers-in-law</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Passers-by</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Passers-by</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Step-brother</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Step-brothers</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Commander-in-chief</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Commanders-in-chief</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Maid-servant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Maid-servants</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Part 2:&nbsp;</strong>in some cases, &ldquo;s&rdquo; comes in every part to make plural.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Lord-justice</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Lords-justices</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Man-servant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Men-servants</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Woman-servant</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Women-servants</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 8:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Besides, adding &ldquo;s&rdquo; in the end can change into plural form.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Book-shelf</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Book-shelves</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Book-case</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Book-cases</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Major-general</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Major-generals</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Poet-laurete</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Poet-lauretes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Forget-me-not</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Forget-me-nots</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 9:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Some singular nouns don&rsquo;t have&nbsp; any plural form, so, it is used in singular..</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Furniture</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Scenery</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Issue</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Bread</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>expenditure</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 9:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Adversely, some words are always used in plural form.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mumps</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Scissors</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Trousers</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Spectacles</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Assets</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 10:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Though some nouns seem like singular, but actually they are plural.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Government</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Peasantry</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>People</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Cattle</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mankind</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 11:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Similarly, some nouns may sound plural though they are singular.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Physics</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Politics</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Ethics</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>News</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Wages</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 12:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>Some words might have the same singular and plural form.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Deer</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Sheep</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Species</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Corps</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Canon</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>&nbsp;</strong></h3>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 12:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>In the case of letters, numbers, and different symbols, it takes an apostrophe and s to alternate it.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Sam, write your g&rsquo;s and y&rsquo;s clearly.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>John, add two 5&rsquo;s and three 8&rsquo;s.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<h3><strong>Rule 13:</strong></h3>\r\n<p>There isn\'t any particular rule for converting the number of pronouns. It&rsquo;s all about memorizing.</p>\r\n<table width=\"762\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>Singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>singular</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><strong>plural</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>I</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>We</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Him/her</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Them</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>My</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Our</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Your</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Your</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Mine</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Ours</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>This</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>These</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Me</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Us</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>That</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Those</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>You</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>You</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>It</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>They</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>He/she</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>they</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>His/her</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>their</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 2.5, 'Number: Rules, Types & Examples', 'number'),
(20, 'Clauses', '<h1>Clauses</h1>\r\n<p>&nbsp;A clause is made out of a collection of phrases that consist of a topic and a finite verb. It carries the most effective one concern and one verb. The concern of a clause may be referred to or hidden, however, the verb has to be obvious and distinguishable.</p>\r\n<p>Types of Clauses</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Independent Clause</li>\r\n<li>Dependent Clause</li>\r\n<li>Adjective Clause</li>\r\n<li>Noun Clause</li>\r\n<li>Adverbial Clause</li>\r\n<li>Principal Clause</li>\r\n<li>Coordinate Clause</li>\r\n<li>Non-finite Clause</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Independent Clause</h2>\r\n<p>Its capabilities on its very own to make a significant sentence and appears just like an everyday sentence.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In a sentence impartial clause may be related via way of means of the coordinators: and, but, so, or, nor, for*, yet*.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>Diya is a wise man.</p>\r\n<p>I like him.</p>\r\n<p>Complete it please. (Subject you is hidden)</p>\r\n<p>I want to buy a desktop, but I don&rsquo;t have enough funds. (Two independent clauses)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Dependent Clause</h2>\r\n<p>It cannot feature on its personal as it leaves a concept or concept unfinished. It is likewise known as a subordinate clause. These assist the impartial clauses whole the sentence. Alone, it cannot shape a whole sentence.</p>\r\n<p>The subordinators do the paintings of connecting the structured clause to some other clause to finish the sentence. In every one of the structured clauses, the primary phrase is a subordinator. Subordinators consist of relative pronouns, subordinating conjunctions, and noun clause markers.</p>\r\n<p>Example:</p>\r\n<p>When I was running futsal, I had a bike accident.</p>\r\n<p>I know the man who stole the watch.</p>\r\n<p>He bought an apartment which was too expensive.</p>\r\n<p>I know that he cannot conquer it.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Dependent Clauses are divided into three types and they are &ndash;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>1. Adjective Clause</strong></p>\r\n<p>It is a Dependent Clause that modifies a Noun. Basically, Adjective Clauses have comparable features as Adjectives which might be of enhancing Nouns and therefore the name, Adjective Clause. These also are known as Relative Clauses and they typically take a seat down properly after the Nouns they modify.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m looking for the student card that went missing last Friday.</p>\r\n<p>Clark is asking for the piano which used to belong to his Uncle Matt.</p>\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<h3>2. Noun Clause</h3>\r\n<p>Dependent Clauses appearing as Nouns in sentences are referred to as Noun Clauses or Nominal Clauses. These frequently begin with &ldquo;how,&rdquo; &ldquo;that,&rdquo; different WH-words (What, Who, Where, When, Why, Which, Whose and Whom), if, whether or not, etc.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>I like what I do.</p>\r\n<p>Gita knows how things work around here.</p>\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r\n<h3>3. Adverbial Clause</h3>\r\n<p>By definition, those are Dependent Clauses appearing as Adverbs. It method that those clauses have the energy to alter Verbs, Adjectives and different Adverbs.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>Tina cycled to the point of panting vehemently.</p>\r\n<p>He went through the comic at a lightning speed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Principal Clause</h2>\r\n<p>These have a Subject (Noun/Pronoun), Finite Verb, and an Object and make complete sentences that may stand by myself or act as the principle a part of any Complex or Compound Sentence. Independent and Principal Clauses are functionally identical however named from distinctive perspectives.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>I know that man.</p>\r\n<p>He can perform every move.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Coordinate Clause</h2>\r\n<p>Two or greater, in addition, critical Independent Clauses joined through Coordinating Conjunctions (and, or, however, etc.) in phrases of Compound Sentences are known as Coordinate Clauses.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>I like clicking photos and he loves editing them.</p>\r\n<p>You prefer playing outdoor games but she always wants to play indoor games.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2>Non-finite Clause</h2>\r\n<p>They include a Participle or an Infinitive Verb that makes the Subject and Verb obvious despite the fact that hidden. In phrases of a Participle, the Participial Phrase takes the region of the Subject or Object of the sentence.</p>\r\n<p>Examples:</p>\r\n<p>He saw the man (who was) staring out of the apartment balcony.</p>\r\n<p>Hearing the gunfire, the children woke up.</p>', 2, 'Clauses: Definition, Types & Examples', 'clauses'),
